  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States and internationally:\n\n1. U.S. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. International Statutes:\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n\n3. Key Provisions:\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establish criminal penalties for money laundering\n- Mandate record-keeping and reporting requirements\n- Create frameworks for investigating and prosecuting money laundering\n\n4. Specific U.S. Criminal Codes:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (laundering of monetary instruments)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (engaging in monetary transactions in property derived from specified unlawful activity)\n\nThese statutes aim to prevent, detect, and prosecute money laundering activities by establishing legal frameworks, reporting requirements, and criminal penalties.",
